e those changes in a self-serving way, and to mobilize new reactionary social logics that might square with the structural and cultural transformations that came with economic liberalization. Crumbaugh's illuminating analysis of the representation of tourism in Spanish commercial cinema, newsreels, political essays, and other cultural products overturns dominant assumptions about both the local impact of tourism development and the Franco regime's final years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCulture and tourismzSpain. 0aFascismzSpainxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxStudy and teaching. 0aTourismxGovernment policyzSpain. 0aTourismxPolitical aspectszSpain. 0aTourismzSpain. 4aArea Studies : Spanish Studies. 4aCommunication : Political Communication. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842689140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438426891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438426891/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles